      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that the state of one cannot be described independently of the other, even when separated by vast distances. It is fundamentally different from classical correlation because, in classical systems, correlations arise from shared history or pre-existing properties (like two coins that were glued together), whereas in entanglement, the properties are undefined until measured, and the measurement of one instantly determines the state of the other. This \"spooky action at a distance\" defies our intuitive understanding of local realism and has been experimentally verified through Bell's theorem tests.\n\nTo put it simply, if you have two entangled particles, measuring the spin of one as \"up\" will instantly cause the other to be \"down,\" regardless of whether they are in the same room or light-years apart. This instantaneous connection is not due to any hidden signal traveling between them, which would violate the speed of light limit, but rather a fundamental feature of the quantum wavefunction describing the entire system.\n\nAs for your midterm, remember that while this sounds like magic, it is the basis for technologies like quantum computing and quantum cryptography. The key takeaway is that entanglement creates a single, unified",
      "source": "target",
