      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so when you say it's like a single unified thing and it's kinda \"spooky,\" is there a specific reason why it feels so weird or \"unexplained\" compared to normal physics? like why can't we just explain it with regular rules?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a great question, and the \"spookiness\" comes from the fact that entanglement seems to violate our everyday intuition about how the universe works, specifically the idea of \"local realism.\" In our daily lives, things are either here or there, and they have definite properties whether we look at them or not (local realism). However, in quantum mechanics, particles don't have definite states until they are measured, and entangled particles act as if they are part of a single, non-local entity. This challenges the classical view that objects are independent and only interact through local forces, which is why it feels so unexplained and counterintuitive.\n\nTo put it another way, if you imagine two entangled particles, they are like a pair of dice that are magically linked so that no matter how far apart they roll, they always show opposite numbers. In classical physics, you could explain this by saying the dice were pre-programmed with their outcomes before they were separated (hidden variables), but experiments have shown that this isn't the case. The outcomes are truly random until the moment of measurement, and the connection between them is instantaneous, which seems to break the rules of causality and space-time.\n\nThis is why physicists",
      "source": "target",
